result.execSummary:
The defendant Joseph C Sutter was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Armed Robbery, a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Court finds defendant eligible for the Challenge Incarceration and Substance Abuse programs only after having served 3 years of initial confinement.

superMiscConds.notes: Restitution due on 14-CF-96 is $447 plus surcharge. Restitution due on read-in case 14-CF-49 is $561.44 plus surcharge.
If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall not enter any establishment where the primary purpose is the sale or service of alcohol.
Defendant shall not have direct or indirect contact with Judith S.; Lake 5 Mobile, Jeffrey E., or Daniel H. 
Defendant shall not associate with anyone involved in the use or sale of controlled substances.

Defendant shall participate in an AODA assessment and all counseling or treatment programs as directed by his supervising agent. 
Defendant shall pay all Dept of Corrections supervision fees.
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample. 
Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or school or a combination thereof. 
Defendant shall submit to weekly random drug screens.
